4. Background Of The Invention

Existing medical devices commonly rely on reactive runtime diagnostics and post-failure troubleshooting approaches for identifying embedded software instability and performance degradation.

Current systems generally monitor static resource thresholds such as CPU usage or memory consumption but do not effectively identify progressive runtime degradation patterns including memory growth trends, latency drift, thread starvation, communication bottlenecks, or correlated subsystem instability.

As embedded medical devices become increasingly software-driven and operate continuously for long durations, intelligent runtime resource optimization and predictive stability analysis become important for improving operational reliability and reducing downtime.

Although runtime optimization technologies exist in general computing and cloud environments, their integration into modular medical device platforms for intelligent embedded runtime monitoring and predictive optimization remains limited.

The proposed invention introduces an AI-assisted runtime optimization framework capable of identifying abnormal operational trends before visible software instability or subsystem failure occurs.

